","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ulcombe, Kent, England":"Ulcombe, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Otterton, Devon, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ulcombe, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Ulcombe, Kent, England","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England"},"en":{"Abt 1301–1347":"about 1301–1347","1300–1326":"1300–1326","1320–1347":"1320–1347","1326–1359":"1326–1359","1327–1359":"1327–1359","1347–Male":"1347–Deceased","1301–1347":"1301–1347","Abt 1326":"about 1326","Abt 1325":"about 1325","Abt 1301":"about 1301","1327":"1327","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ulcombe, Kent, England":"Ulcombe, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Otterton, Devon, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Ulcombe, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Ulcombe, Kent, England","Otterden, Kent, England":"Otterden, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bartholomew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Bertilmew</i>, <i>Bertelmy</i>, a borrowing of the Old French form of the Biblical personal name <i>Bartholomew</i> (from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i>; Hebrew ‘son of Talmai’, said to mean ‘having many furrows’, i.e. rich in land). This was an extremely popular personal name in Christian Europe, with many vernacular derivatives. It derived its popularity from the apostle Saint Bartholomew (Matthew 10:3), who was, among other things, the patron saint of tanners, vintners, and butlers.","As an Irish name, it has been used as an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Pharthaláin</b> (see   McFarlane  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McFarlane","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Pharthaláin</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Parthalán</i>, which is most probably from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). <i>Parthalán</i>, regularly shortened in speech to <i>Parlán</i>, has also been Anglicized as   Bartlett  . Compare   McPartland  .","History: McFarlane is a Scottish clan originally associated with Arrochar on Loch Long. — Robert McFarlane came to NY in 1835 and was editor of <i>Scientific American</i> magazine (1848–65)."]},{"name":"Bara","meanings":["Polish: from a shortened vernacular form of the personal name <i>Bartłomiej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ).","Czech (<b>Bára</b>) and Slovak: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Barbora</i> (Czech), <i>Barbara</i> (Slovak), or possibly of the male personal name <i>Bartoloměj</i> (Czech), <i>Bartolomej</i> (Slovak); see   Bartholomew  .","Hungarian: from a short form of the personal name <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  )."]},{"name":"Barak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Pinhas, Yoram, Avital, Doron, Dov, Erez, Haim, Hanoch, Moshe, Ronit, Shai, Shimon.","Jewish (Israeli): from the Biblical Hebrew personal name <i>Barak</i>, meaning ‘lightning’. The surname mainly represents a Hebraicized form of several original eastern Ashkenazic surnames having similar consonants.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): acronymic surname from the first letters of the Hebrew patronymic phrase <i>Ben Rabi Kalonymos</i> ‘son of rabbi Kalonymos’. The personal name <i>Kalonymos</i> means ‘beautiful name’ in Greek."]},{"name":"Bac","meanings":["Polish (also <b>Bać</b>): perhaps a variant of <b>Bacz</b>, from a pet form of the personal name <i>Bartłomiej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ), occuring in southeastern Poland. Aternatively, it may be a metonymic occupational name derived from <i>baca</i> ‘shepherd’. Compare   Batz  .","French: from <i>bac</i> ‘tub, trough’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name or as a topographic name.","Slovenian: nickname from <i>bac</i> ‘lambkin’. Compare   Batz  ."]},{"name":"Baert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime.","Flemish and Dutch:","from a short form of the personal name <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ), or from the female personal name <i>Baerte</i> or <i>Bartha</i>."]},{"name":"Baczek","meanings":["Polish:","derivative of the personal name <i>Bacz</i>, <i>Bacza</i>, a pet form of <i>Bartłomiej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ).","(<b>Bączek</b>): from <i>bączek</i>, a diminutive of <i>bąk</i>, which variously means ‘horse-fly’, ‘bittern’, or ‘eagle-owl’ (see   Bak  )."]},{"name":"Arko","meanings":["Slovenian: from a pet form of the personal names beginning with <i>Ar-</i>, most likely from <i>Arnej</i>, an old vernacular form of <i>Bartolomej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ).","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Aron</i>, Slavic form of the Biblical name   Aaron  .","West African (Ghana): from an Akan male personal name denoting a first-born boy."]},{"name":"Barac","meanings":["Croatian: from an old pet form of the personal name <i>Bartolomej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ) or of its vernacular variants <i>Bartol</i> or <i>Bartul</i>.","Croatian (<b>Barać</b> and <b>Barač</b>): from a derivative of the personal name <i>Bare</i> or <i>Baro</i>, short forms of <i>Bartolomej</i> (see   Bartholomew  ) or of its vernacular variants <i>Bartol</i> or <i>Bartul</i>.","Serbian (mainly <b>Barać</b>): topographic name derived from <i>bara</i> ‘swamp’ or a habitational name for someone from a place named Bare. It may also be of the same origin as the Croatian names above. Compare   Barach  ."]},{"name":"Bach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Fritz, Klaus, Horst, Johann, Alfons, Bernhard, Erna, Ernst.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a stream, Middle High German <i>bach</i> ‘stream’. This surname is also found in some other European countries, most notably in Denmark and France (Alsace and Lorraine), but also in e.g. the Netherlands, Czechia (see also 5 below), and Croatia.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Bach</i> ‘stream, creek’."]},{"name":"Baczewski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Zygmunt, Bogdan, Bronislaw, Danuta, Jerzy, Zbigniew, Zigmund, Zygfryd.","Polish:","habitational name for someone from a place called Bacze in Masovian Voivodeship."]}]},{"name":"Anabella","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A female name formed from Hannibal."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":14,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":27,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":36,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Anabella Bartholomew was born about 1301, in England. She married Bartholomew de St Leger about 1325, in Ulcombe, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1347, in Ulcombe, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"Abt 1301–1347":"umbes 1301–1347","1300–1326":"1300–1326","1320–1347":"1320–1347","1326–1359":"1326–1359","1327–1359":"1327–1359","1347–Male":"1347–Surnud"